column168: While in transit, (1) box containing (2) 1-gallon bottles of Blue Whale Muriatic Acid (UN1789) became crushed as a result of inadequate preparation for transportation. During the off-loading process, the damaged, crushed product began leaking onto the concrete dock floor; a total amount of 1-gallon. A Contractor neutralized the release using Kolorsafe Liquid Acid Neutralizer before absorbing the liquid and containerizing the spill debris into the proper UN-rated shipping container (a vented 55-gallon fiber drum). Additionally, the pallet in which the load was shipped on was also cut-up and containerized for waste disposal. Lastly, the impacted box that the leaking bottles shipped in was neutralized and containerized for waste disposal. No storm drains, waterways, or soil were impacting by the release.

column168: While in transit, (2) 55DF's containing Sulfuric Acid 1.500 (UN1830) fell over as a result of inadequate preparation for transportation forcing the bung caps to loosen and release 20-gallons of product on the pallet, the trailer floor, and the asphalt beneath the trailer. Contractors neutralized the release using sodium bicarbonate and solidified the liquid with oil dry. The impacted pallet was cut-up and containerized with the rest of the spill debris into (3) 55DF's for waste disposal. No storm drains, water ways, or soil were impacted by the release.

The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XRC experienced a UN2922 Thiocare H101 71% release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4-gallons of product released to a 16’ x 18.5’ area of the trailer floor due to a crack in the tote lid. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Spill-X-A was utilized to neutralize the impacted area. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all impacted rags and PPE into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: Driver alerted Quality Assurance staff that a hazmat package seemed to be giving off a strong smell but there did not appear to be a leak of any kind. column169: Material handlers need to pay attention to the clearances of other freight to help prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column168: Over stack of freight

On 12/5/2023 at approximately 1326, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 5190395 at the staion location in Miami, reporting an hazardous spill .  The shipment consists of a one fiberboard box classified as UN 3373, in which the inner container leaked due to a loose screw-on top.  The shipment suffered total loss and the shipper has been notified.  In compliance with 49 CFR 171.15, this incident was reported to the National Response Center and filed under report # 1385950.

While unloading a pallet of waste from a trailer at Veolia's ten day intransit facility, a Veolia employee heard a pop and realized the forks on the forklift were protruding out of the back of the pallet and punctured a 15 gallon 1H1 drum of flammable liquid located on the pallet behind the one he was moving. Approximately 100 ml of the material leaked out before the hole closed on itself. The employee moved the forklift away from the area and shut it off, then proceeded to contain the spill with absorbent. The employee and the Veolia site manager then donned correct PPE and promptly overpacked the container and cleaned up the spill area.
column169: The Veolia employee needs to be aware of the length of their forks on the forklift in reference to the material they are handling and ensure that their forks do not protrude out the back of the pallet they are working on. Also whenever possible use a spotter to ensure safe loading practices.

column168: on 12/7/2023-Roadrunner notified ERTS that there are 3 -11 gallon metal pails containing paint UN1263, Paint, Class 3, PGII that were discovered to be leaking the in the rear of a freight trailer. It was reported that the release was reportedly caused due to other freight being stacked on the pails. Roadrunner advised that most the released paint had already dried and terminal personnel conducted the cleanup and overpacking operations for the damaged freight and freight trailer. The release was contained to the freight trailer and no soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release. All generated waste was staged on site for pending disposal.

column43: ELAN-Cast P 300 S RTC Low Odor
column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: XPO Logistics terminal LLA experienced a UN1866 ELAN-Cast P 300 S RTC Low Odor release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of material released to the entire trailer floor as well as a 30’ x 20’ area of the concrete lot below due to the trailer wall puncturing the tote. The puncture was patched with wood to stop the release and the material was transferred into a new tote for shipment on. The free-standing liquid material was collected with a drum vac into (2) 55-gallon metal drums. Floor dry was then deployed and worked into the impacted areas and then collected into a third 55-gallon metal drum. The punctured tote was patched with absorbent pads & chemical tape. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal XQC experienced a UN1760 Gunsmoke release from a box containing (2) 2.5-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2.5-gallons of material released from one of the jugs due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents and pH Up neutralizer were utilized to clean and neutralize the release. The empty damaged drum, impacted absorbents, PPE, and impacted cardboard were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: The shipment was discovered during sort operations. A metal can inside of the box leaked liquid that was bubbling, steaming and had corroded away a large portion of the metal can. PH litmus test resulted as strong acid (1). Contents also included a paint brush, a steel brush, and 2 rotary brushes. The metal can was unidentifiable due to the level of corrosion. The contents were neutralized with baking soda and placed into a Steel Salvage Package. The customer was contacted and advised that the shipment contained Pickling Paste. The shipment is being held for FAA investigation.

A fiberboard box with signs of release was discovered during sort operations at the GSOH facility. The fiberboard box contained a steel drum inside and the cap on top of the drum was loose. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package. A new declaration will be obtained for movement.

A FSMA spill agent was called to the sort input for a fiberboard box with signs of a release. The spill agent was told that the fiberboard box was dropped during the unloading process. While investigating the shipment the agent observed that the source of the release came from between the release valve and the cylinder. The fire extinguisher was packaged with molded styrofoam on top and bottom inside of the fiberboard box. All contents were released from the extinguisher and gauge of the release valve reads as empty. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package.
